Exploring Asian Prehistory/Early History

As youâ€™ll see, archaeologists are learning more and more about the development and spread of the Harappan culture in the Indus Valley and surrounding area. Theirs is an ancient writing system that has not, yet, been deciphered.

On the other hand, many traditions of modern-day Chinese culture (not their communist political system, of course) have roots in the early, state-level civilizations there. Also, the Khmer culture, which developed into an empire, is just recently becoming better known to archaeologists. In this lesson, weâ€™ll be considering cultural developments in these regions.

A note on linked web resources

Remember, take the time to check out the web-links I provide. Often, they (along with the textbook) clarify highlights that from the lecture slideshow.

  • Indus Valley cultures
    • Tour some of the great prehistoric/historic civilizations of the Indus Valley. Marvel at the standardization of Harappan urban centers, like Harappa and Mohenjo-Daro.
  • Chinese cultures
    • Not surprisingly, early increases in social complexity and the emergence of state-level society arose along rivers in ancient China. Certainly, the river was important for early peoples there. Though modern-day China is not the same as in the past, Chinese culture shows remarkable continuity over the last two thousand years.

Territories of Dynasties in China. Image by Ian Kiu; licensed under CC BY-SA 3.0.

  • Cambodian cultures
    • One of the largest archaeological sites in the world is Angkor in present-day Cambodia. These sites represent the remains of great capitals of the Khmer Empire.
